The patch mostly implements the epoch-second transition, but consolidation can silently erase out-of-range stored edge timestamps when rendering them back to ISO-8601 for the provider boundary.

Review comment:

- [P2] Reject unrenderable edge timestamps before consolidation — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:4792-4795
  When a caller writes an edge with an epoch outside SQLite's `strftime(..., 'unixepoch')` renderable range (for example any value after `9999-12-31T23:59:59Z`), `epoch_seconds_to_iso8601` returns `None` and these `and_then` calls silently send `null` for `t_valid`/`t_invalid` to the consolidation harness. Since the governed write surface accepts arbitrary `i64` values, this loses temporal evidence at the LLM boundary instead of failing loudly, so consolidation can make a recency decision without the timestamps that are actually stored.
